Each week, our editors select some of the world's most exciting new music. If you hear something you like, add it to your library.
Coldplay - A Head Full of Dreams

Despite courting controversy throughout his career, at heart, Em is all about the art of rhyming. He's an enthralling master of internal and multisyllabic rhymes who's taken mainstream rap to bold new levels of lyrical dexterity. Whether he's dropping motormouth wordplay on hit singles or plunging into more complex structures on album cuts, this is Eminem in his natural element.

Developing the infamous alter ego Slim Shady early in his career, Eminem found a focused outlet for his darkest thoughts—and stirred up plenty of controversy in the process. The divisive persona allows him to air out violent fantasies and drug-fuelled dreams, though he keeps up a cartoonish verve for Slim Shady's delivery to ensure maximum entertainment kicks.

The Louis Vuitton Don has a way of taking over any track he guests on, whether he's bringing his distinctive beats along with him or simply 16 bars of his big personality. A Kanye guest verse can always change the colour on your mood ring, whether he's suave and charming with Estelle, forlorn and lost with Young Jeezy or goofy and amped up with Big Sean.

With his textured harmonies and double entendres, nobody dirties up a pretty track more beautifully than The Weeknd. The Canadian singer's shivering falsetto and break-of-dawn hedonism have graced pop classics by everyone from Kanye to Ariana Grande, bringing a widescreen griminess and lilting sleaze to tracks like “Crew Love” and “Love Me Harder".

As one of the most dynamic performers in hip-hop, Drake casts a long shadow. This collection of lushly appointed R&B and boldly confident rap features his many friends and collaborators. There are introspective forays into romance from Kanye West and J. Cole, clubby boasts from Nicki Minaj and Pusha T and seductions from Bryson Tiller and Miguel.

Kanye West is not only one of pop culture's most polarising figures; he's also one of the most game-changing MCs, producers and trendsetters of the last 20 years. After working the boards for Roc-A-Fella and perfecting his signature production style, Yeezy dropped a string of his own modern classics, starting with The College Dropout and Late Registration. It was his adventurous turns on My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy, Yeezus and Watch the Throne, with JAY Z though that really made him the firebrand he is today, as he continues to change the boundaries of modern hip-hop.

You can't front on Ne-Yo's songwriting skills. The Las Vegas-raised singer has penned crossover smashes for Beyoncé, Rihanna and Mario, but he declared his solo ambitions with his 2006 debut album, In My Own Words. The project went platinum in the US and spawned a run of hits anchored by his passionate vocals. Showing his experimental side, later albums would make moves into the EDM world, but the core of Ne-Yo's appeal is always about the way he combines heartfelt lyrics with pop-friendly production.
Partners in Rhyme: Drake & Lil Wayne

Of the dozens of rappers Lil Wayne has signed to his Young Money imprint, Drake has emerged as the label's greatest discovery and a successor to Weezy's mantle as one of hip-hop's biggest, most prolific stars. Their musical rapport has led to successful tours and countless collaborations, as well as punchlines traded on each other's albums and hits by DJ Khaled and French Montana.
